## Example 4 — Real-World Exponential Models

### Step 1: Set Up the Problem

**SUBSCRIPTIONS:** A club starts with 40 members and grows by 20% each year. Model the number of subscribers over 5 years.

Initial value: [a = 40]
Growth rate: [b = 1.20]
Function: [f(x) = 40(1.20)^x]

### Step 2: Answer the Question

After Year 4: [f(4) = 40(1.20)^4 ≈ 40(2.0736) ≈ 82.94] subscriptions

**SHOES:** Athletic shoes cost $58.17 in 2018 and increase 5.1% annually. Model the cost after [t] years.

[f(t) = 58.17(1.051)^t]

After 25 years: [f(25) = 58.17(1.051)^25 ≈ 58.17(3.473) ≈ $202.17]

### Step 3: Compound Interest Applications

**MONEY:** Sunil deposits [P] dollars at 3% annual compound interest.

[A = P(1.03)^t]

After $500 deposit for 10 years: [A = 500(1.03)^10 ≈ 500(1.344) ≈ $671.96]

To find when the account doubles: [2P = P(1.03)^t → 2 = (1.03)^t → t = ln(2)/ln(1.03) ≈ 23.4] years

## Example 5 — Exponential Growth vs. Decay

Determine whether each function represents exponential growth or exponential decay.

### Step 1: Apply the Criteria

* If [b > 1]: exponential growth
* If [0 < b < 1]: exponential decay

[f(x) = 7^x] → [b = 7 > 1] → growth
[g(x) = 0.99^x] → [b = 0.99 < 1] → decay
[h(x) = (2/3)^x] → [b = 2/3 < 1] → decay
[j(x) = (5/4)^x] → [b = 5/4 > 1] → growth
[k(x) = 0.75^x] → [b = 0.75 < 1] → decay
[m(x) = 1.02^x] → [b = 1.02 > 1] → growth

